Here are both approaches:

**1. Register the route** in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public AppShell()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
}
```

**2. Navigate from ProductListPage** (e.g., in a tap command):

```csharp
// Approach A: String query parameter
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");

// Approach B: Pass the full object
var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
{
    { "product", product }
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
```

**3. Receive on the ViewModel** — implement `IQueryAttributable` to handle both cases:

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public string ProductId
    {
        get => _productId;
        set => SetProperty(ref _productId, value);
    }

    public Product Product
    {
        get => _product;
        set => SetProperty(ref _product, value);
    }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: string parameter from query string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service using ProductId...
        }

        // Approach B: full object via ShellNavigationQueryParameters
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            Product = product;
            ProductId = product.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String query param | `ShellNavigationQueryParameters` |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | `$"route?key={value}"` | `new ShellNavigationQueryParameters { { "key", obj } }` |
| **Data types** | Strings only | Any object |
| **Serialization** | Values become strings; parse on receive | No serialization; cast directly |
| **Use when** | Simple IDs, flags, small values | Complex objects you already have in memory |

> **Tip:** Always `await` the `GoToAsync` call — fire-and-forget causes race conditions. And make sure `ProductDetailsPage` sets its `BindingContext` to `ProductDetailsViewModel` (via DI or code-behind) so `ApplyQueryAttributes` is invoked on the right instance.
